ly in regard to Cambodia, Kosovo, East Timor, Bosnia and the Middle East.Key Featurescritically interrogates the theory, experience, and current outcomes of liberal peacebuildingincludes five empirically-informed case studies: Cambodia, Kosovo, East Timor, Bosnia and the Middle Eastfocuses on the key institutional aspects of liberal peacebuilding and key international actorsassesses the local outcomes of liberal peacebuilding  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aLiberalism. 0aNation-buildingvCase studies. 0aNation-buildingxCase studies. 0aNation-building. 0aPeace-buildingvCase studies. 0aPeace-buildingxCase studies. 0aPeace-building. 4aPolitics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aFranks, Jason, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074864206940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748642069423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748642069/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK